{{about||the town|Hadrut|the rayon of [[NKAO]]|Hadrut Rayon (NKAO)}} {{Infobox settlement <!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions --> | name = Hadrut | native_name = Հադրութ | type = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh|Province]] | image_map = NKR locator Hadrut.png | seat_type = Capital | seat = [[Hadrut (town)|Hadrut]] | leader_title = Governor | leader_name = Valery Gevorkian | area_total_km2 = 1,877 | area_water_percent = Negligible | area_rank = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh#By_area|Ranked 2nd]] | population_total = 13,163 | population_footnotes = <ref name="census">[http://census.stat-nkr.am/nkr/1-4.pdf Census]</ref> | population_as_of = 2013 | population_rank = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh#By_population|Ranked 5th]] | population_density_km2 = auto | postal_code_type = [[Republic of Artsakh postal codes|Postal code]] | postal_code = | area_code_type = [[FIPS 10-4]] | area_code = | iso_code = | website = [http://gov.nkr.am/hy/regions/details/51/ Hadrut Province] }} [[Image:Hadruthos.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The Hadrut Regional Hospital]] '''Hadrut Province''' (Հադրութ in [[Armenian language|Armenian]]) is a [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh|province]] of the ''de facto'' [[Republic of Artsakh]]. The Republic has [[Political status of Nagorno-Karabakh|limited international recognition]]. It is ''de jure'' part of the Republic of [[Azerbaijan]]. It forms the southern border of Nagorno-Karabakh, and one of the most [[mountain]]ous parts. Villages are primarily found along two river valleys and scattered in lower elevations on the very southern fringe. Excavations of the [[Azykh Cave|Azokh Cave]] show that humans have inhabited this area for tens of thousands of years, and the region has a rich history.
Hadrut province has 30 communities of which 1 is considered urban and 29 are rural. The most important problems are drinking and irrigation water, and internal communication roads. Some villages are lacking a telephone network and some have difficulties with watching Armenian TV channels. More than 340 people of Hadrut Region fell victim during the [[Nagorno-Karabakh war]].{{cn|date=June 2017}} Nearly 30% of its area has been ruined and burnt several times.<ref>[http://archive.hetq.am/eng/society/0610-hadrut.html Hetq.am Now the time has come for building] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531152833/http://archive.hetq.am/eng/society/0610-hadrut.html |date=2011-05-31 }}</ref>
==Sites of interest== * Town of [[Hadrut (town)|Hadrut]] * Monastery of Spitak Khatch (Սպիտակ Խաչ; White Cross), 14th century * [[Gtichavank]] monastery (Գտիչի վանք), 1241–1248 * Anapat Church (Անապատ եկեղեցի), 13th century, near the village of Togh (Տող) * [[Khodaafarin Bridges]]
==See also== * [[Dizak]] * [[Arajamugh]]
